  <div class="col-md-7">
    <p> The flight from Singapure to Sydney was just as relaxed as the flight before. When I arrived in Sydney Airport, I did not have to enter but could also stay in the transit area. I spent the waiting time skypend in the caf&eacute; with a view of the Sydney skyline. In Sydney I noticed for the first time that my sense of balance came confused. I always had this strange swaying feeling like after a long show -off shipping. </p>
    <p> The last flight to Auckland was a bit shaky. As a small compensation, we each got an ice cream for dessert. Once again 30 minutes before the planned arrival time, we landed in Auckland. There I had to partially unpack my bag for the first time. I had to show my riding gaps. The friendly controller praised my cleaning skills and I was able to pack up again. He hadn't even sprayed the gaiters because they must have smelled quite strongly for disinfectant. </p>
    <p> The bus to the hotel was also ready in front of the exit. As if he had only waited for me, it started as soon as I got on. 50 minutes later I arrived in the hostel where Sam was already waiting for me and even got me a SIM card. But maybe more about that later. </p>
  </div>
</div><div class="row margin-bottom-10">
  <div class="col-md-12">
    <p> In any case, I am happy that I don't necessarily have to fly over the next 3 weeks. There were 5 full meals on at least 4 flights in 3 different aircraft. My seat was changed twice and a flight was a bit shaky. On the way I was almost 2 days and crossed 10 time zones and flew into spring from autumn. I got on the plane on Tuesday at 18.25 and got out on Thursday at 2:30 p.m. Nevertheless, it was relatively relaxed. </p>
